Thanks for the upload! We are supposed to merge the files in the following order: Scalia Kennedy Thomas Ginsburg Breyer Roberts Alito Sotomayor Kagan.

But I think the files Kennedy.Warhead1, Roberts.Warhead1 and Sotomayor.Warhead1 are incomplete. Here's why:
All the files are supposed to merge nicely into a base64-encoded file. Note it's made of ascii lines with 64 chars per line. For instance, the last line of the file Thomas.Warhead1 is
QMIYRWaSfVsohy3wprV4
and the first line of the file Ginsburg.Warhead1 is 
F+tAyZDBx/8K6uo/dBXGjKdkyozYDT4qXgUvUwh6lKGf
so when you merge the two, you get a complete 64 chars line.

However, merging kennedy with thomas, roberts with alitos, and sotomayor with kagan doesn't make a 64 chars line. Considering all the files size are 157286400 bytes except kennedy, roberts, and alitos which are smaller, I highly suspect those three are incomplete. (And I think kagan is smaller just because it's the last file.)

If I guessed right, then it's not really the uploader's fault because it's just how the files are on the last working mirror. Anonymous, what the hell...

I had correct file sizes verified by other anons before uploading this torrent as I too had the same belief. These files are certainly full copies of what was on the mirrors. The only thing we could come up with was that possibly part of the decryption package fills in the missing parts of said files. This would make sense as a solid prevention method to stop the decryption of the files before the release of the key.

I confirm that in the other torrent (https://thepiratebay.sx/torrent/8070181), the lines on all the split points have 64 chars. The other torrent is the right thing to download.

You can run the following unix command to print the lines on the split points:
for file in Scalia* Kennedy* Thomas* Ginsburg* Breyer* Roberts* Alito* Sotomayor* Kagan*; do head -n 1 $file; tail -n 1 $file; done
All the lines that gets printed (except the last one) should have the same 64-chars length.
